Preheat your oven to 200°C. Thinly slice the @chestnut mushrooms{225%g}. Trim the
tops from the @green beans{80%g}, then chop into thirds. Finely chop the
@coriander{1} (stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a
#garlic press{}).

Pop the @cauliflower florets{300%g} onto a #baking tray{}, drizzle over a splash
of @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle on half the
@ground turmeric{1} and rub into the cauliflower.

> TIP: Use gloves to do this if you don't want your hands to get stained by the turmeric.

Roast the cauliflower on the middle shelf of your oven until golden and charred
at the edges, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn half way through cooking.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{100%ml} in a large #saucepan{} over high heat. When
the water is boiling, pour in the @basmati rice{150%g}, @salt{0.25%tsp} and the
remaining turmeric. Cover with a #lid{}, lower the heat to medium, cook for
~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for
another ~{10%minutes}.

> Tip: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{} in another large saucepan over medium-high
heat. Add the mushrooms. Cook, stirring frequently until the mushrooms have
browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the @easy ginger{}, garlic and
@pasanda style seasoning{1%packet} (don't add it all if you don't like spice).
Stir and cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @water{} and the @vegetable stock powder{1}, stir to dissolve the stock
and bring to the boil. Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, add the green
beans and @raisins{40%g} and pop the lid on. Simmer until the beans are tender,
~{6-8%minutes}. Remove the lid, add the @creme fraiche{112.5%g} and simmer for
~{3-4%minutes} more. Taste and add salt and pepper if necessary. Get ready to
serve.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir in half the coriander. Share the rice
between your plates, then spoon the mushroom curry over and around. Arrange the
cauliflower florets on top and finish with a sprinkling of the remaining
coriander. Enjoy!